sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1500006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: MutL from BBa_K1500997 was cut out and inserted downstream into the IPTG-GFP backbone plasmid (K1500006).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The nonmutated, wild-type MutL gene cloned into the IPTG-GFP plasmid for characterization of mutation rate, verification of fucntionality, etc. MutL, long with MutS and MutH, initiates repair cascade by recognizing base mismatches/indels of up to 4 bp (dam-directed mismatch repair). It requires the mutation E32K to gain its active dominant negative mutagenic form.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kevin Yang

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0032
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Weak1 RBS based on Ron Weiss thesis. Strength is considered relative to <bb_part>BBa_B0030</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0031</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0033</bb_part>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix ("RBS-2" in figure 4-14 of thesis).

Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1500002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: IPTG promoter was cloned from registry plasmid BBa_J04500, RBS.3 was designed into the primer for cloning IPTG, and these were cloned into reporter GFP, cutting the front two cut sites.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Contains an IPTG-sensitive promoter (BBa_J04500), with RBS.3 (BBa_00032), and reporter GFP (E0040) downstream. This part was primarily used as the initial plasmid into which mutator genes were cloned and site-directed mutagenesis was conducted. Also, it was intended to be the plasmid in which mutator genes were assembled in combinations before cloning the entire combination out into the AroF-mCherry-LVA backbone.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The back two cut sites may be cut and mutator genes PCR'd from wild-type may then be inserted into this plasmid.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kevin Yang

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1500997
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: PCR'd from genomic sequence of DH5-alpha E. coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Along with MutS and MutH, initiates repair cascade by recognizing base mismatches/indels of up to 4 bp (dam-directed mismatch repair). This is the wild-type version; it requires the mutation E32K to become active.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kevin Yang

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: GFP (mut3b) [note that this part does not have a barcode]
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: jcbraff

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LacI
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The Plac insert was PCR'd from the MG1655 strain of E.coli K12.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Inverting regulatory region controlled by LacI (BBa_C0010, BBa_C0011, etc.)

The pLac regulatory region is a 243 base-pair sequence with standard BioBrick prefix and suffix sections on its ends. It contains two protein binding sites: CAP, which is generally present in E.coli and is assocciated with cell health and availability of glucose., and LacI, the Lac inhibitor BBa_C0010 which binds in an dimerized cooperative manner to inhibit the transcription of the protein that follows. In the presence of lactose or IPTG, an analog of lactose, LacI is unable to correctly bind and inhibit transcription. This allows BBa_R0010 to be used as a inverter or as a detector of lactose or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LacI binds to this regulator. This part is incompatible with species containing active LacI coding regions. Lactose and IPTG disable the operation of LacI and this regulator. This part is incompatible with environments containing lactose or lactose analogs.
